<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome Outreach</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      background-color: #f4f6f8;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }
    header {
      background-color: #2a6f97;
      color: white;
      padding: 30px 20px;
      text-align: center;
    }
    nav {
      background-color: #468faf;
      text-align: center;
      padding: 15px;
    }
    nav a {
      color: white;
      margin: 0 15px;
      text-decoration: none;
      font-weight: bold;
    }
    nav a:hover {
      text-decoration: underline;
    }
    section {
      background-color: white;
      margin: 20px auto;
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 10px;
      max-width: 900px;
    }
    h2 {
      color: #2a6f97;
    }
    footer {
      background-color: #468faf;
      color: white;
      text-align: center;
      padding: 15px;
      margin-top: 30px;
    }
    img {
      display: block;
      margin: 10px auto;
      max-width: 100%;
      height: auto;
    }
    ul {
      padding-left: 20px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
  <h1>22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome Outreach</h1>
  <p>This website was created to support patients, families, and caregivers by providing clear and accessible information.</p>
</header>

<nav>
  <a href="#about">About</a>
  <a href="#symptoms">Symptoms</a>
  <a href="#diagnosis">Diagnosis</a>
  <a href="#treatment">Treatment & Support</a>
  <a href="#resources">Resources</a>
</nav>

<section id="about">
  <h2>About 22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome</h2>
  <p>
    22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome is a genetic condition caused by a small missing piece of chromosome 22. 
    It affects each person differently and can impact multiple systems in the body. It is sometimes 
    referred to as DiGeorge Syndrome.
  </p>
  <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8e/Chromosome_22.svg" alt="Chromosome 22 illustration">
</section>

<section id="symptoms">
  <h2>Symptoms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Heart defects</li>
    <li>Speech and learning difficulties</li>
    <li>Immune system differences</li>
    <li>Feeding or growth issues</li>
    <li>Behavioral or developmental delays</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="diagnosis">
  <h2>Diagnosis</h2>
  <p>
    Diagnosis is typically made through genetic testing, usually a blood test. 
    It can be identified before birth or during early childhood depending on symptoms.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="treatment">
  <h2>Treatment & Support</h2>
  <p>
    There is no single cure, but treatments help manage symptoms. These can include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Heart surgeries if needed</li>
    <li>Speech and developmental therapies</li>
    <li>Educational and learning support</li>
    <li>Regular medical checkups and follow-ups</li>
    <li>Family and community support programs</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="resources">
  <h2>Resources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.22q.org/" target="_blank">The 22q11.2 Foundation</a></li>
    <li><a href="https://www.cdc.gov/genomics/disease/22q11.2.html" target="_blank">CDC Overview of 22q11.2</a></li>
    <li>Local pediatric genetic specialists and support groups</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<footer>
  <p>Created by Alisson Betancur for 22q11.2 patient outreach</p>
</footer>

</body>
</html>
